00:22:02,377 --> 00:22:05,998
And I don't know if he wants to share them, but I thought I would open that up for you, buddy.

284
00:22:06,018 --> 00:22:13,262
I think you're all waiting for my thoughts and responses.

285
00:22:14,951 --> 00:22:21,620
So I read this and, you know, in general I could pick apart a few words here and there, but I think it's a fair statement.

286
00:22:23,442 --> 00:22:25,725
You know, I, I think.

287
00:22:26,814 --> 00:22:32,058
We constantly have to do work to ensure positive outcomes in all of our communities.

288
00:22:32,458 --> 00:22:37,001
I think that entails numerous trainings and reforms in policing.

289
00:22:37,602 --> 00:22:46,328
And one of the statements made in this, one of the remarks in this statement basically says that, you know, you call for the, just trying to read it while I'm looking at the screen here.

290
00:22:48,245 --> 00:22:49,766
Proper training and resources.

291
00:22:50,046 --> 00:22:58,129
And despite a lot of the reforms that were placed on police since 2020 and a lot of the changes, we really are policing in Massachusetts has come a long way.

292
00:22:59,150 --> 00:23:02,451
But there's not a whole lot of resources sometimes to support that.

293
00:23:02,611 --> 00:23:05,772
And unfortunately, policing sometimes resources means money.

294
00:23:06,373 --> 00:23:13,396
But I can tell you that I've met with numerous police groups since this.

295
00:23:13,756 --> 00:23:16,197
And together, nobody wants these outcomes.

296
00:23:17,821 --> 00:23:24,746
You know, when police interact with individuals in mental health crisis, we want the best of the outcomes.

297
00:23:25,006 --> 00:23:33,792
And sometimes, I mean, it is, if someone could invent the perfect resolution and solution to these, the police would be the first to sign up for that.

298
00:23:35,153 --> 00:23:39,496
And unfortunately, I dance around some of these issues.

299
00:23:39,516 --> 00:23:41,277
I don't know all the detailed facts of this.

300
00:23:41,297 --> 00:23:42,458
I don't think any of us know that.

301
00:23:44,379 --> 00:23:45,020
It's hard.

302
00:23:45,080 --> 00:23:57,010
We supply, in the city of Medford, we have three co-response clinicians, and we're going to take advanced steps in the city of Medford starting on April 3rd, where they will be out in the police cars responding to these immediately.

303
00:23:57,070 --> 00:24:00,013
So it's not like a situation happens that we have to call somebody to the scene.

304
00:24:00,033 --> 00:24:00,894
They will be with us.

305
00:24:02,335 --> 00:24:03,976
So there's a lot of advances happening.

306
00:24:04,397 --> 00:24:07,119
This is a tragic case.

307
00:24:09,463 --> 00:24:22,097
spoken with a number of Cambridge police officers, my own police officers, the outcomes like this are things that we want to work with the community to prevent and look for them not to happen ever.

308
00:24:23,451 --> 00:24:36,425
They do happen though, right and we know that and we recognize that and we recognize that there's not going to be a switch that we could turn off tomorrow and kind of solve these problems but I think you have committed partner in the police to work to resolve some of these instances.

309
00:24:37,086 --> 00:24:44,434
So, I mean, as I said before, I think I could argue over a few of these words I think the intent of this statement and on behalf of the Human Rights Commission is

310
00:24:45,255 --> 00:24:47,297
is just, and it could go out there.

311
00:24:47,317 --> 00:24:50,261
I still debate back and forth.

312
00:24:50,281 --> 00:24:57,048
I've had a long standing commitment to when police matters come up to kind of, kind of abstain from voting from them.

313
00:24:57,188 --> 00:25:04,996
But I think even if I take that stance, I think my statements, public statements on record here today, stand sort of in support of that.

314
00:25:05,377 --> 00:25:07,018
And again, I

315
00:25:10,106 --> 00:25:11,246
I think it's fine.

316
00:25:11,267 --> 00:25:25,798
I think there's an understanding, though, that I'm really curious as to the outcome when the final statements made by Cambridge Police and the investigation that is ongoing by the district attorney's office and the independent judge, I'm curious as to some of the details.

317
00:25:25,878 --> 00:25:31,082
And we learn from that and how we can do better, not just in medicine, but in the entire community of policing.

318
00:25:31,122 --> 00:25:32,703
So it is tragic.

319
00:25:33,444 --> 00:25:44,889
I do know that I met shortly, very shortly thereafter, and I believe you all know this, but Syed was a member of the Islamic Cultural Center in Medford, and I met with them.

320
00:25:45,029 --> 00:25:46,550
I met with some of his friends over there.

321
00:25:47,130 --> 00:25:49,571
I had very good conversations with them.

322
00:25:52,965 --> 00:25:56,567
you know, very sad conversations too, you know, that go back and forth.

323
00:25:56,587 --> 00:25:59,149
So my condolences do go out to the family.

324
00:25:59,569 --> 00:26:08,494
And I will say on the record though, because it's tragic all around, my condolences go out to the Cambridge Police Department and the officers, and nobody wants to do this.

325
00:26:08,534 --> 00:26:12,356
I can stress to you that nobody comes to work as a police officer who wants to cause harm.

326
00:26:12,716 --> 00:26:15,218
We want to do good, and we strive to do good.

327
00:26:15,338 --> 00:26:20,641
And if messages like this can push the community members to support the police for the resources and the training,

328
00:26:21,835 --> 00:26:28,617
and I'm all for it, so.

329
00:26:30,178 --> 00:26:36,920
Can I add something, just a side note, not really relevant, well, it is hopefully relevant.

330
00:26:38,921 --> 00:26:49,925
There is an effort in Cambridge, speaking of resources, there is an effort going to the city council to have them actually

331
00:26:51,107 --> 00:27:04,838
hire, add three or more positions of unarmed trained civilians to handle such cases when mental health is concerned.

332
00:27:06,259 --> 00:27:07,960
I don't know what the outcome will be.

333
00:27:08,040 --> 00:27:20,190
I don't think it has been decided yet, but perhaps in the future we can maybe have a similar effort here in Medford to do something like that.

334
00:27:21,617 --> 00:27:28,579
And I will say that that's part of our co-response to train clinical social workers who will be responding alongside with police.

335
00:27:28,599 --> 00:27:35,181
And if the situation, because the police, we've learned one thing all along, the police are going to get called regardless.

336
00:27:35,201 --> 00:27:37,441
When someone's in crisis, they're going to be calling the police.

337
00:27:37,541 --> 00:27:40,682
And we're now thinking along the lines of we can bring additional support.

338
00:27:41,022 --> 00:27:46,864
And if need be, we can leave a clinical social worker on scene and the police can leave if it's truly a mental health crisis.

339
00:27:47,544 --> 00:27:49,725
I do caution in the grand scheme of talking about this

340
00:27:50,685 --> 00:27:58,192
Sometimes there is violence that's associated with mental health and those are the things those are the issues that we have to look at hard.

341
00:27:58,972 --> 00:28:03,676
Someone who's trying to inflict self harm or somebody out in the public who could harm others.

342
00:28:05,175 --> 00:28:11,121
it's hard for an unarmed civilian clinical worker to deal with that while at the same time that the police are trying to protect the public.

343
00:28:11,161 --> 00:28:27,537
So there's, there's some really, I don't want to call them gray areas, but there's some really peak areas that, that, that with the two cross and, and, and really create crisis that I don't know that, that we're going to get to right away, just by simply having civilians who can kind of, unarmed civilian can handle things because

344
00:28:28,863 --> 00:28:31,647
I mean, there's certain things that we can't just walk away from.

345
00:28:32,107 --> 00:28:40,579
I mean, I will tell you today I met with numerous police chiefs, and a lot of the conversation is about what do you do when you have

346
00:28:41,628 --> 00:28:53,833
barricaded and armed or unarmed civilians and whether or not they can impact the safety of others and what it actually is going to be causing or resulting in a change in police response sometimes.

347
00:28:53,873 --> 00:28:58,875
So there's a lot of conversation on this going and it is all for the good and it's all for the positive.

348
00:28:59,255 --> 00:29:10,179
And I mean, it just goes to that we are doing that in Medford now and we're hoping for better outcomes every single day that we go out there and improve.

349
00:29:12,931 --> 00:29:15,894
Yeah, Chief, I think you touch on some really important points there.

350
00:29:16,135 --> 00:29:29,870
And one of them being that, you know, anytime you try to implement a change or remedy for a situation, you want to be treating the effects, or I'm sorry, the cause rather than the symptoms, right?

351
00:29:30,370 --> 00:29:32,453
And I think that fundamentally speaking,

352
00:29:33,150 --> 00:29:49,004
Police having to deal with individuals who are having mental health crises, violent or nonviolent, is a symptom of lack of resources being available outside of policing and the justice system for those individuals to rely on.

353
00:29:49,665 --> 00:29:53,288
So bringing this actually back full circle to the letter,

354
00:29:54,117 --> 00:30:04,982
I wonder if it might be and this is a very small tweak certainly doesn't need to be entered into the, the beautiful writing has already taken place, but just mentioning.

355
00:30:06,175 --> 00:30:12,040
giving police and communities the resources they need to support these individuals.

356
00:30:12,660 --> 00:30:24,610
Because exactly to your point, the police are only called when there is the expectation that somebody could be harmed or is in some way in danger.

357
00:30:24,630 --> 00:30:34,018
And if we can keep folks experiencing mental health crises out of situations where they themselves or the members of their community are in danger by empowering

358
00:30:34,718 --> 00:30:47,483
other organizations within the community to provide support to those individuals, I think that's really going to be exponentially more effective than anything the police are able to do, because it's not their main focus.

359
00:30:48,024 --> 00:30:56,547
And I don't mean that at all as a negative, just thinking about the purpose of policing in society as it has evolved to exist.

360
00:31:01,109 --> 00:31:02,049
Can people hear me?

361
00:31:02,090 --> 00:31:03,050
My screen is frozen.

