00:31:04,685 --> 00:31:05,585
Oh, we can hear you.

363
00:31:06,986 --> 00:31:11,407
And so my thoughts align with what's already been said, but maybe take it a step further.

364
00:31:11,427 --> 00:31:20,910
And I actually watched the video that sort of, you know, had the content around his this incident.

365
00:31:22,143 --> 00:31:28,685
And I felt like by the time a moment like that happens, there's already been several sort of systemic failures.

366
00:31:29,466 --> 00:31:37,008
And so I wonder if there is space to discuss like the role of mental health supports and how one might seek them out.

367
00:31:38,109 --> 00:31:39,749
I believe this person was a student.

368
00:31:39,789 --> 00:31:50,773
So were there university supports available or are there cultural conversations that can be taken place that like allow for space to consider mental health supports as part of like a health

369
00:31:51,317 --> 00:31:52,838
kind of initiative for the individual.

370
00:31:52,858 --> 00:31:58,082
And also in full disclosure, when Muneer sent me the email, I was like, this is great.

371
00:31:58,202 --> 00:31:59,223
Thank you for writing it.

372
00:31:59,343 --> 00:32:00,103
I appreciate you.

373
00:32:00,523 --> 00:32:03,826
So these are just recent thoughts that I'm having while listening to folks speaking.

374
00:32:06,260 --> 00:32:07,221
Thank you for sharing.

375
00:32:07,981 --> 00:32:09,722
Sorry, if I could just add one point to that.

376
00:32:11,183 --> 00:32:24,911
I think sometimes when we have these tragic incidences, we look from the incident forward, what happened at the incident forward, and we need to start getting people in crisis into care before that, before they rise to the level of the police.

377
00:32:25,351 --> 00:32:30,174
And when we study these and we look at, say, we question, oh, did the police have body-worn cameras?

378
00:32:30,194 --> 00:32:30,714
Did they do this?

379
00:32:30,754 --> 00:32:31,315
What's the action?

380
00:32:31,335 --> 00:32:33,196
But we really need to go backwards and tie it to

381
00:32:34,027 --> 00:32:52,462
You know, where is the care and how do we get individuals like sayeed into care and professional care prior to this so it doesn't come to crisis level and the police are called and I think there's a totality of it right we can't just look at a one thing we have to kind of spread that out, and then we have to look for community support to provide that care.

382
00:32:53,963 --> 00:32:54,884
pre crisis.

383
00:32:56,604 --> 00:33:09,391
And I'm trying to think of the, I think it was a Boston Globe and references in the past but Boston Globe in 2016 wrote a really great article about the increase in individuals.

384
00:33:11,051 --> 00:33:15,372
under mental health crisis and involvement with the police and the police officers and the police departments.

385
00:33:15,892 --> 00:33:20,434
And they tie it all the way back to early 1990s when they shut down a lot of the mental health institutions.

386
00:33:20,854 --> 00:33:22,814
And then what have we done since then?

387
00:33:22,834 --> 00:33:25,375
A lot of it's outpatient care, and that's great.

388
00:33:25,415 --> 00:33:30,956
I mean, I'm not calling for institutionalizing individuals, but there has to be another level of care.

389
00:33:31,376 --> 00:33:37,378
And what did happen was, because I started in the 90s, and what did happen is

390
00:33:38,605 --> 00:33:48,009
The individuals who were charged with responding to mental, to the individuals with mental health were the police officers first, and then the emergency rooms, right, or the EDs as they call them now.

391
00:33:48,369 --> 00:33:51,751
And that was the chain of care for many of these individuals.

392
00:33:51,811 --> 00:34:02,595
And families didn't have a lot of places to turn, so they would call the police, the police would send them to the EDs, and it became sort of, I'm not gonna call it a vicious cycle, in a lot of cases it did, because that was the only care they got.

393
00:34:02,675 --> 00:34:04,316
And then they'd go home and maybe,

394
00:34:05,137 --> 00:34:09,326
with some medication adjustments or whatever, but they would always end up where we're dealing with the same sort of individuals.

395
00:34:09,667 --> 00:34:14,116
We are getting better with that as not just police departments, but as communities.

396
00:34:14,984 --> 00:34:18,106
But I fear that, you look around, hospitals are closing.

397
00:34:18,566 --> 00:34:22,348
And all these institutions where we can get care for individuals are closing.

398
00:34:22,368 --> 00:34:32,855
So in general, I think Massachusetts, I think this country needs to start thinking about mental health care on a different level and trying to figure out how to deal with this.

399
00:34:33,335 --> 00:34:39,599
It's the lifelong issue that we've all been dealing with in our generations is health care and how to provide better health care for everybody.

400
00:34:39,939 --> 00:34:40,679
But it must stop.

401
00:34:40,899 --> 00:34:42,140
And every time we have these issues,

402
00:34:43,981 --> 00:34:47,082
uh, in discussions, we should always just look at it in both texts.

403
00:34:47,102 --> 00:34:51,784
Like what can the police do better, but what can we do as a community to prevent this from getting to the police first?

404
00:34:52,004 --> 00:34:52,184
Right.

405
00:34:52,344 --> 00:35:10,270
And, and so, uh, I'm always in full support of those kinds of conversations and they're not going to be easy solutions though, because that those are, um, you know, the, the healthcare is, uh, is somewhat in crisis when it comes to mental health.

